# Connect Product Line Engineering and Work Model, Operating Model:
    ## Product Line Engineering has two sub-functional subsets:
        - Domain Engineering - Advance the Domain Capabilities
        - Win Engineering- Advance the Win Capabilities (Win Enablement)

    ## Engagement Engineering has three sub-functional subsets:
        - Solution Engineering - Compose a solution for a customer using one or more Product Lines
        - Studio Engineering - Build customer-specific apps, portals, back-office tools, etc. (usually customer's IP)
        - Pre-sales Engineering - Build Proposals and Proof of Concepts for prospects and customers using one or more Product Lines
    --------------------------------


# Notes (updated DR-036):
    - **Sealed System Versions** and **certified Product Versions** are deployable via System and Product Deployment Specifications. Component Versions are build outputs that compose into System Versions.
    - CI/CD produces Component Versions; assembly produces System Versions; certification produces Product Versions. Deployment specifications and execution are Run Track concerns (Operating Model).

    - Component Version update → System Version assembly → System Deployment Specification update → System-scoped deployment → verification; Product Version certification → Product Deployment Specification → product-scoped deployment when needed.
    - If a deployment is not acceptable because deployed products will become incompatible, the Change Request / deployment is not permitted.

    - Run and Win Tracks may introduce operational Systems via Build Track (same versioning chain). Product Specification (Technical) catalogs all Systems for a product.
    - Customer-specific solutions compose Product Versions and deployment specifications per tenant/environment — not a separate Package layer.

    - Data Migration and Schema Changes. In enterprise systems, database schema changes and data migrations are a significant category of engineering work that often requires coordination across Systems and careful rollout planning (rollback of schema changes is harder than code rollback). The model doesn't explicitly address this — it would likely be a Story or Technical Task, but the unique rollout/rollback characteristics of schema changes might warrant acknowledgment.

